{"type":"message","id":"4ecbcd05","parentId":"357b9f3e","timestamp":"2026-05-02T03:43:38.588Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the PID 29665 is OpenClaw's gateway process running on the Mac. It's using a LOT of memory (2.4GB+) and 100% CPU consistently. That's a significant resource consumer. But that's OpenClaw itself - the gateway that runs the whole team.\n\nThe question is whether this is normal or problematic. Let me think about this:\n\n1. OpenClaw gateway (node process) - consistently ~100% CPU, ~2.4GB+ memory - This is the main AI team coordinator\n2. duetexpertd - Apple's on-device AI processing (Apple Intelligence) - using ~25MB RAM but 48% CPU at times\n\n\n3. Various Chrome processes - each using 150-260MB RAM\n4. corespotlightd - Apple's Spotlight indexing - using 46MB RAM but running for 8+ hours\n5. WindowServer - normal macOS window manager\n6. Other system processes\n\nOn an 8GB MacBook Air, this is a LOT of memory pressure. The fact that there's only ~200MB of free memory with 7.4GB used and 2.4GB compressed means the system is heavily relying on memory compression and swap.\n\nThe real concern is OpenClaw itself consuming 2.4GB - that's unusually high for a gateway process, though it could be storing conversation history in memory. I should look at what other processes are actually running and what's consuming the most resources.","thinkingSignature":"12ac6aa9af622886478e3832592f34f0b93d87dc21bc1fd17eb9cac5c44ac56a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_9sirwjtpllhj_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ps aux 2>&1 | head -1; ps aux 2>&1 | grep -v grep | grep -v \"top\" | grep -v \"ps aux\" | sort -rnk 3 | head -20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1417,"output":368,"cacheRead":52992,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":54777,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777693413290,"